    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "This paper tries to show that a black hole governed by Modified Gravity (MOG), when buffeted by a special kind of gravitational wave, behaves differently from one in ordinary General Relativity \u2014 emitting radiation in an irregular pattern and eventually stopping its evaporation at a cold, stable remnant. The review board found the central idea interesting, but identified multiple severe technical errors in the derivations that undermine the main results. The most critical problems are that the paper's own equations for the black hole's horizon contradict each other between sections, and that the proposed stable remnant cannot actually form under the theory's own rules. The paper as written should not be relied upon for quantitative conclusions.",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "The paper derives a dynamical apparent horizon, modulated surface gravity, and Hawking luminosity for a Schwarzschild-MOG black hole perturbed by an \u2113=0 scalar breathing mode, then argues GSL preservation via Raychaudhuri order-separation and a dual-pathway information-paradox resolution. Reviewers across two adversarial cycles identified: (1) a fatal internal inconsistency between the horizon formulas in Sections II (h-dot dependent) and III\u2013IV (h dependent), propagating through the entire thermodynamic chain; (2) that for a spherically symmetric \u2113=0 mode the null-congruence shear tensor \u03c3_ab vanishes identically, removing the claimed positive-definite driver of irreversible entropy growth in the GSL proof; (3) that in standard STVG at fixed \u03b1 both M_G and Q_G scale linearly with M, so Q_G/M_G is conserved under mass evaporation and the extremal bound is never approached \u2014 invalidating the remnant endpoint; (4) a self-contradiction between invoking the quasi-adiabatic approximation for the Stefan-Boltzmann luminosity and simultaneously claiming adiabaticity breakdown drives non-thermal emission; (5) that the \u2113=0 long-wavelength approximation used to derive the horizon shift is incompatible with the QNM-frequency imprinting claimed in Section V. The STVG perturbation ansatz (pure angular sector) is also not verified against the full linearized field equations. No Bogoliubov or stress-tensor calculation supports the non-thermal emission claim."
    }
